    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-06T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-06T02:00:00-05:00" n="1060"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1060">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5034 (China) Thrift Corp./34: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-06T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 6, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 6—5:48 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>29. Embassy’s 28, October 5, 1 p.m.<note n="6" xml:id="d1060fn6">Not
                        printed.</note> Following urgent telegram has been received from American
                    Consul General at Harbin.<note n="7" xml:id="d1060fn7">Walter A. Adams.</note>
                </p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“37, October 6, 11 p.m. Embassy’s October 5, 1 p.m.</p>
                    <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>There is much excitement in Harbin over suspension of Thriftcor Bank
                            which remained closed yesterday.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>I believe prompt action is desirable by the American authorities. I
                            suggest that United States Court for China be requested to appoint
                            liquidator at once.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Does Court desire any preliminary action by this Consulate
                            General?”</item>
                    </list>
                </quote>
                <p>Judge Helmick<note n="8" xml:id="d1060fn8">Milton J. Helmick, Judge of the United
                        States Court for China.</note> informed me on October 4 prior to my
                    departure from Shanghai that he had told Shanghai attorneys for bank that as
                    there was no American interest shown and as registration with Consulates had
                    been denied he saw no reason for Court taking <pb facs="1214" n="1102"
                        xml:id="pg_1102"/> jurisdiction. I agree with Judge Helmick that we should
                    not assume the responsibility for bank’s liquidation and would like so to
                    instruct Harbin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
